				<td colspan="2"><span>So its me (32 Bard) my good friend (34 Cleric) and one of his friends (34 Shammy). We do a norm collect just to feel each other out. Now, they're pretty twinked, and I'm decently geared, and my Cleric friend says, &quot;You're gonna love the Shammy's proc.&quot; Turns out she'se using a Barbarian Spiritist's Hammer (250 dd cold Proc). So I ask her what her Dex is, trying to decide between Anthe, and Chant of Battle. She tells me its around 170 and goes, &quot;Good enough for ya? Wanna compare other stats?&quot; She then proceedes to buff herself and herself only, angrilly CHAing me when I ask for it. Right off the bat I'm wondering what's going on, and as my friend tells me its 3 am for them, just ignore the standoffishness, she mutters, &quot;It seems like arrogance is a bard trait...&quot; We continue on to mmc and start fighting.. the fights are going quickly, but were taking heavy damage. Soon I notice something is up and ask, &quot;Are you slowing?&quot; She isn't. She'se nuking. And she'se at full life. I ask her if she knows how to canni dance. She doesn't, so I ask if I could teach her after the LDoN, that it's a cool Shammy thing, and nets you more mana. She says sure, and makes a couple snide comments. After the LDoN completes, she immediately gates and leaves the group, leaving my cleric friend who says, &quot;Man who the heck are you to tell her how to play her class? She hasn't gotten us killed yet&quot; I've had a 65 Shammy. I know how to play them. And those who know how to play their bards better than me? I listen when they give advice, solicited or unsolicited. Should I have just not said anything and let her find out in about 10 levels that her gear won't save her forever?</span></td>
