			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Aggrivating LDoN<a name="46942"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 18 04 3:16 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Ehh had a whole thing about criticism written up but I didn't feel it added to the discussion so I deleted it....maybe it wouldn't have been such a bad idea. I'll try to re-produce it.
<br />

<br />
In my opinion theres really two factors that contribute to how a person takes criticism, real world or EQ. Those factors are how secure the person is in themselves and how humble they are.
<br />

<br />
1. People who are very humble and very secure are those that take criticism well and ask thoughtful questions to get the best out of the advice they receive.
<br />

<br />
2. People who are very humble but not too secure in themselves tend to ask a lot of questions. They are less likely to disagree and more likely to try new things. They learn more through trial and error.
<br />

<br />
3. People who are not very humble and very secure are the ones who don't actively seek advice, they try things on their own and are generally hit or miss. They are less likely respond to criticism in a productive manner.
<br />

<br />
4. People who are not very humble and not very secure are those that abhor criticism. They become defensive and feel threatened. They usually exhibit &quot;holier than thou&quot; behavior to mask their anxiety. These are also the people who like big flashy things like 6k crits or powerful race cars, and if in possession of such will go out of their way to make you aware of it. These people are slow learners, they tend to need a strong stimulus in order to change their ways.
<br />

<br />
I think your shaman friend falls into the last category. Slightly insecure about their character as to become defensive when you asked a simple question about their stats and are of little humility when they obviously did not want your advice. Nothing you could have done would have changed the outcome in my opinion. They will either figure it out themselves or get it beat into them, or quit.
<br />

<br />
**Im no psychologist but I like to reminisce about human behavior sometimes as its pretty funny if you think about it...</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
