			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Aggrivating LDoN<a name="47345"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 21 04 12:55 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">The question that I was getting at though is, is it better to be quiet (since her playing wasn't directly affecting my efficiency) or try to impart knowledge? Seems like I always hear people complaining about people not accepting constructive criticism, but then again I also hear a lot of &quot;I wish there were less morons in the game.&quot;</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
In your situation I might have said something like &quot;Hey, I have a 65 shaman and really love playing him, it's cool to meet someone else enjoying the class.  Lemme know if you have any questions I can answer for ya&quot;
<br />

<br />
Basically, starting by being positive and letting them know that you're willing to help them if they want, but not pushing advice if it's unwelcome.
<br />

<br />
Realize also that people are much more open to advice if a) you know them well, or b) something bad has actually happened and they're asking why it happened.  It sounds like your adventure was going well enough and this shaman was a stranger, so it's not that surprising that your advice wasn't well received.
<br />

<br />
I would also add that the phrase &quot;constructive criticism&quot; is so often misused that I would never use those words - in my experience, people who can actually offer genuine constructive criticism are greatly outnumbered by people who throw out &quot;it's just constructive criticism, don't be so defensive&quot; as an excuse to be a jerk. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
